 Sultan's government be made to support British objectives, or would it always favour France or Russia?Promised Lands shows how what started as a geopolitical contest became a drama about diplomatic competition, religion, race, and the unforeseen consequences of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aOrientalismzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAbolitionism.  aAeschylus.  aAnglo-Persian War.  aAnglo-Russian.  aAnglo-Turkish War (1807-09).  aAppeasement.  aArab Revolt.  aArabs.  aBernardino Drovetti.  aBlood libel.  aBritish Influence.  aCaliphate.  aCatholic emancipation.  aCharles Napier (Royal Navy officer).  aChristian Identity.  aChristianity.  aConcert of Europe.  aContinental Navy.  aCounterforce.  aCrimean War.  aCrusades.  aCult of the offensive.  aDisarmament.  aDivan.  aDruze.  aEastern Question.  aEdict.  aEdward Said.  aEgypt (Roman province).  aEgyptian Government.  aEgyptians.  aEntente Cordiale.  aEuripides.  aFranco-Ottoman alliance.  aFrench campaign in Egypt and Syria.  aFrench intervention in Mexico.  aFrench invasion of Russia.  aGeneral Treaty.  aGeorge Canning.  aGiovanni Battista Belzoni.  aGod.  aGrand Vizier.  aGreat power.  aGreek War of Independence.  aGrenville ministry.  aHejaz.  aHoly Alliance.  aHussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca.  aImperialism.  aIndian Rebellion of 1857.  aIslam.  aJewish political movements.  aJews.  aKhedive.  aLatin Patriarchate of Jerusalem.  aLetter of appointment.  aLevant Company.  aMassawa.  aMiddle East.  aMuhammad Ali of Egypt.  aNapoleon III.  aNapoleon.  aNapoleonic Wars.  aNestorianism.  aNestorius.  aNew Centre.  aOrder of the Crescent.  aOrientalism.  aOttoman Empire.  aOttoman d